    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. Parse their timestamp columns with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For metric.csv: group by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute (1) total data point count, (2) global P95 of the value column, and (3) min and max timestamps. For trace.csv: group by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute the same aggregates (count, P95, min/max ts). For log.csv: group by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute the same aggregates (count, P95, min/max ts). Return three compact tables (metrics, traces, logs) each limited to top 20 rows sorted by count descending. Also return the list of unique cmdb_id values found across all three files and a brief row count for error_logs.csv (timestamp parsed) and the earliest/latest timestamps in error_logs.csv. Do not print full time series. Limit numeric precision of P95 to 6 decimal places."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregate scan: we computed global P95 per series across the full available time range. The telemetry contains many service series (including many ts-admin-* and ts-travel*). The error_logs file appears empty (row_count = 0). Traces show high row_count for ts-travel2-service and ts-travel-service related call counts; logs show large row_count numbers for ts-travel-service, ts-travel2-service, ts-auth-service and ts-route-service. The set of unique cmdb_id values includes the candidate services for root-cause (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service), so we can proceed to focused metric-based anomaly detection for those five services within the incident window. None of the prior results directly identified a metric breach for those five services yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series (do NOT filter by time yet). Then parse timestamps to UTC and filter metric rows to only those where cmdb_id is one of: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service'] AND timestamp is within the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in that filtered window, report a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_global, points_in_window, anomaly_count_where_value>=p95_global, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (or NaT if none). Also return the list of unique kpi_name values observed for these five services. Sort the table by anomaly_count desc and limit to top 20 rows. Round p95_global to 6 decimals."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) across full series and filtered metrics to the incident window. Key signals: ts-order-service:error was flagged because its global P95 is 0 and every in-window point met >=P95 (25/25). Other notable anomalies with small counts: ts-order-service:socket (3 anomalies), ts-train-service:socket (3 anomalies), and several ts-auth-service KPIs with 2 anomaly points each. Error logs file was empty and traces show high call counts for ts-travel-service/ts-travel2-service but trace error_rate fields were 0. At this stage we cannot conclude root cause: ts-order-service:error may be a false positive due to P95=0 baseline, and other KPIs show only a few isolated points. We need to inspect actual metric values and the temporal structure (consecutive anomaly segments) for the top candidate component-KPIs to determine whether there are true faults (consecutive breaches with meaningful severity) or false positives.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For the following component-KPIs: ['ts-order-service|error','ts-order-service|socket','ts-train-service|socket','ts-auth-service|cpu','ts-auth-service|socket'] do the following:\n1) Compute p95_global for each (use the full series for that (cmdb_id,kpi_name)).\n2) Parse timestamps to UTC and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC.\n3) For each component-KPI produce a compact summary table row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_global (6 decimals), points_in_window, min, max, mean, std (values rounded to 6 decimals), anomaly_count where value >= p95_global, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (or NaT).\n4) Additionally, for each component-KPI identify consecutive anomaly segments (value >= p95_global) within the window and return up to the first 10 segments per KPI as: segment_start_utc, segment_end_utc, length_in_points, max_value_in_segment. Limit the total output to a compact structured text (tables) and do not print full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics for the five candidate services in the incident window. Results: ts-order-service|error shows every in-window point equals its global P95 (p95_global=0) but all values are 0 (likely a false-positive by the >=P95 rule). Other metric signals are short-lived spikes: ts-order-service:socket (three short bursts), ts-train-service:socket (short bursts), ts-auth-service cpu/socket (one- or two-minute spikes). Traces previously showed high row_counts for ts-travel-service and ts-travel2-service but their trace error_rate values were 0. Error_logs is empty. At this stage metrics alone don't point clearly to a single persistent resource failure — the persistent 'anomaly' on ts-order-service|error is not a meaningful deviation (values equal zero). According to the diagnosis workflow, we should now use trace-level anomaly checks (including looking for drops in row_count or increases in error_rate/duration) to (a) confirm propagation and (b) localize the most downstream faulty service. Therefore the next step is to run a bounded trace analysis over trace.csv focused on traces that target the candidate services (and travel services observed with high traffic) to detect anomalies defined as: for duration/error_rate series value >= global P95, for row_count series value <= global P5. This will help find downstream faulty services and whether traffic drops or error increases align with the metric spikes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the full series (do NOT filter by time yet). Then parse timestamps to UTC and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC. Keep only trace_name entries that contain any of these substrings: 'to_ts-auth-service','to_ts-order-service','to_ts-route-service','to_ts-train-service','to_ts-travel-service','to_ts-travel2-service'. For each remaining (cmdb_id, trace_name) report a compact row with: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_global (6 decimals), p5_global (6 decimals), points_in_window, anomaly_count (where for trace_names containing 'row_count' anomaly = value <= p5_global; otherwise anomaly = value >= p95_global), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (or NaT). Sort results by anomaly_count desc and limit to top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We explored metrics, traces, and logs for the incident window. Metric analysis: ts-order-service|error shows a persistent ‘‘anomaly’’ because its global P95 equals 0 and all in-window points are 0 (likely a threshold artifact / false positive). Other metric signals are short-lived spikes: socket spikes on ts-order-service (~03:39–03:42) and ts-train-service (~03:32 and 03:38), and brief cpu/socket spikes on ts-auth-service (~03:24, 03:28, 03:39). Trace analysis found many trace.error_rate series with global p95=0 so they were flagged across the window (likely not useful by itself). Importantly, trace row_count series for ts-admin-travel-service and ts-admin-travel2-service show a few low-count anomalies beginning ~03:29:00 UTC (row_count <= global P5). Error_logs is empty and log.error_count values in log.csv are all 0 for the candidate services; log.row_count is high for travel services. At this point metrics alone do not identify a clear, large, consecutive fault in one of the provided candidate services. Traces show traffic drops to travel-related services at ~03:29 and widespread zero-based error_rate flags starting ~03:20 (but likely a threshold artifact). We need to look at per-trace duration and row_count time-aligned within the window for traces that target the candidate services (auth/order/route/train/travel/travel2) to see which service shows meaningful deviations (consecutive duration increases or row_count drops) that could localize a downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series (do NOT filter by time). Then parse timestamps to UTC and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC. Keep only trace rows where trace_name contains any of: 'to_ts-auth-service','to_ts-order-service','to_ts-route-service','to_ts-train-service','to_ts-travel-service','to_ts-travel2-service'. Also restrict trace_name to the metrics types: 'duration_mean','duration_p95','row_count','error_rate'. For each remaining (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce a compact row with: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_global (6 decimals), p5_global (6 decimals), points_in_window, count_anomalies (anomaly defined as value >= p95_global for duration/error_rate; value <= p5_global for row_count), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (or NaT). Sort rows by count_anomalies desc and limit output to top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed threshold calculation and metric + trace scans for the incident window. Summary of findings so far:\n- Metric analysis: The persistent \"anomaly\" on ts-order-service|error is likely a threshold artifact (global P95 = 0 and all in-window values = 0). Other metric signals are short-lived spikes: socket spikes on ts-order-service (~03:39–03:42) and ts-train-service (~03:32 / 03:38), and brief cpu/socket spikes on ts-auth-service (~03:24, 03:28, 03:39). None of these form long, severe (>50% above threshold) consecutive faults except the ts-order:error zero-baseline case.\n- Trace analysis: Many trace.error_rate series have global p95 = 0, leading to widespread flagged points around 03:20 UTC (likely a normalization/threshold artifact). More actionable is row_count drops targeting travel-related traces (ts-admin-travel-service -> to_ts-travel-service and to_ts-travel2-service) with a few low-count anomalies beginning ~03:29:00 UTC.\n- Logs / error_logs: earlier aggregate indicated log.error_count values are zero across candidate services and error_logs.csv appeared empty.\nWhat can be derived: metrics alone do not point to a single clear service-level fault among the five candidate services. Traces indicate travel-related traffic reduction beginning ~03:29 and a system-wide trace.error_rate flagging starting ~03:20 (but zero p95 means treat cautiously). To disambiguate, we must perform focused log analysis for the candidate services to see if logs show errors or traffic drops that corroborate traces and metrics (and to confirm whether travel services are impacted). This will help decide the root-cause service and reason (e.g., socket error, network packet loss, or resource issue).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. For log.csv: compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full series (do NOT filter by time). Parse timestamps to UTC and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC. Restrict cmdb_id to: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce a compact row with: cmdb_id, log_name, p95_global (6 decimals), p5_global (6 decimals), points_in_window, anomaly_count (define anomaly as: for log.row_count use value <= p5_global; for log.error_count use value >= p95_global), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (or NaT). Sort by anomaly_count desc and limit to top 20 rows. Additionally, report the number of rows in error_logs.csv within the incident window and return up to the first 10 rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) from error_logs.csv in that window (if any). Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds, filtered data to the incident window, run metric analysis (candidate services), run trace analysis (focused on candidate targets), and run log analysis. Findings so far: (1) Many zero-baseline global P95/P5 values (for error_rate and log.error_count) produce widespread flagged points starting ~03:20 UTC — likely a normalization/threshold artifact and must be treated with caution. (2) Metrics show only short-lived spikes on socket/cpu for ts-order-service, ts-train-service, and ts-auth-service; none form long, severe consecutive faults except ts-order-service|error which is all zeros (artifact). (3) Traces indicate travel-related row_count drops (ts-admin-travel-service -> to_ts-travel-service and to_ts-travel2-service) with earliest low-count at ~03:29:00 UTC (3 low-count points each). (4) Logs show simultaneous log.error_count flagged across multiple services around ~03:20 UTC but error_logs.csv is empty. \n\nWhat can be derived: There is a clear cross-service signal beginning ~03:20 UTC (error_count / error_rate flags), but those flags are suspicious because thresholds are zero. More actionable is the travel-related trace row_count drop at ~03:29 UTC. To localize the root cause we need to verify which service in the call path shows meaningful, consecutive anomalous behaviour (duration increase, error_rate increase, or sustained row_count drop) rather than zero-threshold artifacts. The next diagnostic step must extract the actual anomalous trace points (not full series) for travel-related traces so we can see exact timestamps, values, and whether anomalies are consecutive and severe.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series (do NOT filter by time). Then parse timestamps to UTC and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 03:17:05 to 2024-01-24 03:47:05 UTC. Keep only rows where trace_name contains 'to_ts-travel-service' or 'to_ts-travel2-service' AND trace_name ends with one of: 'duration_mean','duration_p95','row_count','error_rate'. For each row in the window that meets an anomaly condition (for duration_mean/duration_p95/error_rate: value >= p95_global; for row_count: value <= p5_global) return a compact table limited to the first 50 rows with columns: timestamp_utc, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, p95_global(6 decimals), p5_global(6 decimals). Sort by timestamp_utc ascending."
}

